</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="196" pageNumber="197">
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Donn. Sm." baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia oligocephala" order="Myrtales" pageId="196" pageNumber="197" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oligocephala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="196" pageNumber="197">Conostegia oligocephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized by its leaf abaxial surface which is obscured by whitish and ferrugineaous trichomes, sessile flowers subtended by persistent bracteoles, non calyptrate calyx, and linear calyx teeth. This species has been confused with 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia plumosa" order="Myrtales" pageId="196" pageNumber="197" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="plumosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="196" pageNumber="197">Conostegia plumosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia xalapensis" order="Myrtales" pageId="196" pageNumber="197" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="xalapensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="196" pageNumber="197">Conostegia xalapensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can be distinguished from them by the lack of a calyptrate calyx and presence of evident calyx teeth. It is also similar to another non-calyptrate specie, 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="L. O. Williams" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia fulvostellata" order="Myrtales" pageId="196" pageNumber="197" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fulvostellata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="196" pageNumber="197">Conostegia fulvostellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. See the latter species for differences between the two. The molecular phylogeny places 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Donn. Sm." baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia oligocephala" order="Myrtales" pageId="196" pageNumber="197" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oligocephala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="196" pageNumber="197">Conostegia oligocephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as sister to 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia incurva" order="Myrtales" pageId="196" pageNumber="197" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incurva">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="196" pageNumber="197">Conostegia incurva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with strong support. The two share a similar leaf indument and calyx teeth but are easy to separate based on inflorescence and flower size.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
